<DOCNO> AP890419-0022 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
senate sponsors of a compromise bill to 
control airborne toxic chemicals say they expect stiff opposition 
despite growing information on poisons in the nations air 
this bill will be critized by some for going too far and by 
others who dont think it has gone far enough senate majority 
leader george j mitchell dmaine said tuesday after he and 11 
other senators introduced the legislation 
the bipartisan and diverse group said their language remains 
subject to hard bargaining but emphasized they have a consensus on 
how to control the estimated 27 billion pounds of poisonous 
chemicals released into the atmosphere each year 
the environmental protection agency in its first such 
compilation said april 12 that the toxic air emissions are among 
more than 22 billion pounds of toxic wastes sent into the air 
water and land each year 
the legislation to control toxic emissions into the atmosphere 
represents a major compromise for lawmakers pushing for new clean 
air legislation this year senate clean air sponsors said they will 
introduce the other components of their legislation in coming 
months proposals to bring metropolitan areas in compliance with 
air quality standards and language to control acid rain 
the air toxics compromise would require companies emitting 10 
tons or more of any airborne toxic chemical to install the best 
available control technology 
the environmental protection agency would set emissions 
standards for industries releasing the chemicals but to encourage 
polluters to make immediate and largescale reductions they would 
be granted exemptions if they used technology that achieves a 90 
percent cutback in emissions by the end of 1992 
if technology did not achieve the required reduction a company 
would have to meet tough emissions limits based on a chemicals 
risk of causing cancer or other illnesses 
the legislation would replace a system that has regulated only 
seven toxic chemicals out of nearly 300 emitted into the air 
the epa is currently required to assess the risk of each 
chemical and then develop chemicalbychemical emissions standards 
designed to protect public health with an ample margin of safety 
the assessment for each chemical takes several years and when 
the epa has made proposals the agency has been sued on grounds it 
went too far or not far enough 
the bill also would direct epa to establish a national urban air 
toxics program to reduce the release of toxic chemicals from motor 
vehicles wood stoves dry cleaners and gas stations 
in a provision to prevent catastrophic accidents the bill would 
require epa to list 50 extremely hazardous substances facilities 
handling those materials would have to complete reviews to identify 
potential accidents a chemical safety board would be established 
to investigate accidents and make recommendations for preventive 
measures 
sen max baucus dmont the manager of senate clean air 
legislation this year told reporters there is a public health 
crisis that will worsen if we dont act 
ed barks spokesman for the national clean air coalition said 
the environmental groups in the organization believe the bill needs 
improvements 
he said that under the bill the epa could take between five and 
13 years to set standards for emission reduction for polluters who 
fail to qualify for the exemption that timetable is too long he 
said 
announcing the compromise were sens david durenberger rminn 
frank lautenberg dnj john breaux dla baucus john chafee 
rri quentin burdick dnd daniel patrick moynihan dny 
mitchell john warner rva bob graham dfla joseph lieberman 
dconn and james jeffords rvt 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

