<TEXT>
in a costcutting move the soviets are bringing 
their cosmonauts home from their space station mir next week and 
leaving it unmanned until august the stations deputy flight 
director says 
viktor d blagov said no technical problems had cropped up in 
the 3yearold orbiting complex that is the showcase of the soviet 
space program 
his comments tuesday came a day after the magazine aviation week 
and space technology reported in the united states that mir had 
developed a serious electrical power problem 
mirs solar batteries blagov said were experiencing some power 
loss but that it was within expected levels and was not causing any 
problem 
blagov said plans to keep soviets aboard the station 
continuously were abandoned for several reasons 
by this action we are of course economizing some sum which 
can be used for other purposes he said by telephone from the 
mission control center in kaliningrad north of moscow 
he did not identify the other purposes but the public has 
called for the untold millions of rubles spent on space to be 
diverted toward ending chronic shortages of consumer goods and food 
blagov said soviet scientists were swamped analyzing information 
gathered from mir which was launched feb 20 1986 they now must 
pause to review what we have accomplished and decide whats 
next 
