<TEXT>
a coalition of television producers unions 
and station owners says it will fight any attempt by abc cbs and 
nbc to reenter and dominate the lucrative syndicated tv market the 
networks were forced to leave in 1983 
the motion picture association of america on tuesday announced 
that a 207member coalition would stand in the way of the networks 
if they attempt to gut the socalled financial interest and 
syndication rule 
mpaa president jack valenti said the coalition was putting the 
networks on notice that we will not lag or hesitate to defend the 
rule and hold it in place 
a 1983 consent decree between the networks and the justice 
department forced the networks out of the syndication business 
that agreement expires in 1990 and the networks and producers have 
been negotiating to try to reach a new accord without further 
government intervention 
but the talks have reached an impasse the coalition to preserve 
the financial interest and syndication rules said 
independent producers say they owe their very existences to the 
1983 decree under which the networks were allowed to keep the 
programs they broadcast for four years and then return them to 
producers for sale to independent tv stations and network 
affiliates 
hit programs such as the cosby show and miami vice can 
make many millions of dollars in this syndication market 
unlike before the networks were barred from holding any 
financial interest in programs they license from outside producers 
but the networks take all advertising revenues from a programs 
network run 
the program producers on the other hand are paid a licensing 
fee by the networks typically 1 million to 15 million for an 
hourlong program that usually doesnt meet the total costs of the 
production 
but the producers can profit enormously in syndication with a 
hit show 
the rule is working the coalition said the number of 
independent tv stations has grown so has the number and quality of 
producers creating programming for network and syndicated 
exhibition meanwhile the three major networks remain 
profitable and dominant 
an nbc spokesman in new york joe rutledge said the rules 
which first were adopted by the federal communications commission 
in 1970 have had exactly the opposite effect from what was 
intended 
he said the fcc in 1983 recommended the rules be repealed 
because the rules had concentrated power in the hands of a small 
number of studios rather than adding to diversity 
jay kriegel senior vice president at cbs in new york said he 
hoped the addition of independent producers to the studionetwork 
negotiations will be good for the talks 
he said the hollywood studios who are in the present coalition 
were trying to consolidate their gains against the networks in 
numerous areas half the mpaa members are in direct competition 
with the networks kriegel said every leader in that community 
is now going into our business very aggressively 
the coalition includes the mpaa the alliance of motion picture 
and television producers the association of independent television 
stations the communications workers of america the directors 
guild of america general mills the international alliance of 
theatrical stage employees the screen actors guild and the 
consumer federation of america 
