<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney and other 
nato defense ministers today began talks likely to center on the 
politically sensitive issue of upgrading shortrange nuclear 
missiles in europe 
cheney attending his first gathering of the 16nation north 
atlantic treaty organization was expected to press the allies for 
a new and stronger commitment to us plans to modernize the 
weapons 
i think it is important that we go forward to modernize that 
force he told reporters aboard his air force jet en route 
brussels he reiterated american opposition to eastwest 
negotiations on reducing shortrange weapons in europe 
now is the time i believe to move forward on conventional 
nonnuclear forces he said 
germany belgium and some other european nations want nato to 
indicate its willingness to open talks on shortrange nuclear 
weapons with the sovietled warsaw pact 
officials said it was unlikely the defense ministers would 
discuss the matter in any depth at this twoday meeting there 
appears to be a desire on the part of the allies officials said 
to show cohesion in advance of a may summit between president bush 
and other nato leaders 
the ministers also were not scheduled to make any key decisions 
on modernization which is strongly opposed in some european 
countries but they will be asked to reaffirm their backing to 
plans to upgrade the current lance surfacetosurface missile 
the united states contends it needs a strong signal from the 
allies to lobby congress for money to continue a 
researchanddevelopment program for the weapon 
bush and other nato leaders will meet at the end of may and 
discuss the modernization plans as part of a blueprint designed to 
guide the alliance in arms control and force planning in the coming 
years 
the modernization issue has become increasingly sensitive in 
recent months 
chancellor helmut kohl of west germany has said he wants to 
delay a decision on deployment of the new missile until 1991 or 
1992 after elections in his country 
belgium recently added to the uncertainty by saying it too 
wanted decisions put off until the early 1990s 
a us diplomat said decisions on producing and deploying the 
missile were not expected for several more years 
the lance missile introduced in 1972 will become obsolete in 
1995 
the missile has a range of 60 miles and its replacement would be 
extended to more than 250 miles just under the limits of the 
intermediaterange nuclear forces treaty the accord eliminates 
us and soviet landbased missiles with ranges of about 300 to 
3400 miles 
there are currently 88 lance launchers most of them in west 
germany 
us gen john galvin commander of natos european forces 
argued for modernizing the shortrange missile force in an article 
tuesday in the international herald tribune 
he said the sovietled warsaw pact has undertaken an extensive 
modernization program for shortrange nuclear forces during the 
1980s 
galvin has drawn up a report that says replacing the missile 
will allow the western alliance to make substantial reductions in 
nuclear artillery the study was to be discussed by the defense 
ministers 
nato contends it needs a nuclear arsenal as a deterrent to 
offset the enormous superiority the east has built up in 
conventional or nonnuclear weapons 
the nato members are canada the united states belgium 
britain denmark germany greece france iceland italy 
luxembourg the netherlands norway portugal spain and turkey 
france which is not part of natos integrated military 
structure does not attend the nuclear discussions iceland takes 
part as an observer 
