<TEXT>
a nationwide shortage of math and 
science instructors probably will continue into the next century 
but alternative teacher training programs help offset the 
shortfall a study has found 
the united states will need about 20000 new math and science 
teachers each year for the next decade says linda darlinghammond 
lead author of a rand corp study on teacher education which was 
released tuesday 
the study found that postgraduate training programs for career 
switchers retirees and other nontraditional teacher recruits 
produce about 2000 science and math instructors a year or 10 
percent of the shortfall 
less than half of the demand will be met by graduates of 
traditional education programs by 1992 the study adds 
ms darlinghammond noted that the national science teachers 
association estimates that about 30 percent of the people teaching 
math or science are not fully prepared 
quite often a physical education teacher will be asked to 
teach biology because some administrators view the curriculum 
requirements as similar she said 
this produces recurring problems with poor student achievement 
in the sciences and math she said 
our very best math students the top 5 percent of our 
students score below the average for students in japan and 
china ms darlinghammond said 
if we dont improve our ability to produce large numbers of 
welltrained people in scientific and technical fields we will not 
be able to compete economically in the international marketplace 
ms darlinghammond said 
the biggest obstacles reported in recruiting and retaining good 
science and math teachers are similar to those for teachers in 
general relatively low pay student disciplinary problems poor 
student motivation excessive paperwork and assignment to 
nonteaching chores 
the rand study redesigning teacher education opening the 
door for new recruits to science and mathematics training 
generally found that there are two ways to increase the supply of 
entrants to an occupation 
increase the benefits or attractions to the field or reduce 
the costs of entry efforts to improve teacher salaries and working 
conditions are intended to address the first of these and 
nontraditional programs attend to the second of these strategies 
they aim to lower the financial and opportunity costs of preparing 
to teach 
nontraditional programs focus on training people who did not 
consider math or science teaching while they were in college 
but a rand survey of 64 such programs comprising most of the 
programs nationwide found significant differences in some cases 
programs have been closed for lack of funding since the survey was 
done two years ago 
the extent of study required varied from as few as 16 weeks to 
two years or more requiring completion of as few as nine course 
credits to as many as 45 some provide student teaching experience 
but not all 
</TEXT>
