for someone who wants to be known as the education president 
george bush has pretty feeble proposals in his first education 
budget 
both in his inaugural address and again last week the president 
declared that the nation has more will than wallet but when it 
comes to making progress in education washington will have to open 
its wallet wider than bush proposes 
the administrations education package has worthwhile goals 
unfortunately to pay for these aims the president proposes 441 
million not much by washington standards and certainly not enough 
to make a dent in any of his targeted areas much less in all of 
them 
instead of throwing pennies at such problems bush would be 
better advised to restore some of the cuts made by the reagan 
administration 
but if bush wants to make his mark on education he will 
have to rethink how much the nation can spend on improving its 
schools and whether it can afford not to 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april 12 
aberdeen sd american news on the minimum wage 
when we first considered the minimum wage issue we thought it 
was obvious that the wage should be raised after reading articles 
from several sources however we discovered there is no easy 
answer 
an american economics association survey found that 90 percent 
of its members agree that a minimum wage increase results in more 
unemployment among young and unskilled workers 
these jobs will be lost because employers will decide to have 
fewer employees since their wages will be higher 
the worst part of this situation is that those the higher wage 
is intended to help those with the fewest job skills will be 
the first to be unemployed 
it is impossible to tell those earning minimum wage that they 
are making enough money but the decision may easily turn into a 
choice between a lowpaying job or no job either way no one wins 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april 12 
the newsreview roseburg ore on housing policies 
there is ample evidence that secretary jack kemps department of 
housing and urban development is fostering a new and important 
spirit of cooperation with congress 
for instance kemp has expressed great interest in a 
comprehensive housing bill introduced in the senate earlier this 
month with broad bipartisan support 
huds new policies emphasize the importance of helping 
lowincome families to work actively toward solving their own 
housing problems rather than being the passive recipients of 
federal largesse 
part of kemps master plan is the creation of federal 
enterprise zones to attract businesses to povertystricken inner 
cities and rural areas 
another important part of the overall housing plan is the 
concept of urban homesteading which enables people living in 
public housing to buy their own homes 
hud is now working on a plan to provide temporary accommodation 
for the homeless in unused federal buildings throughout the nation 
 
these commonsense policies bring selfrespect dignity and 
above all hope to a section of the population which too often 
finds itself trapped in a cycle of despair and poverty 
</TEXT>
