seven prominent antiapartheid 
leaders detained for almost three years without charge were 
released today from a prison in the southern city of port elizabeth 
some of them were taken into custody at the beginning of the 
current state of emergency in june 1986 and the rest were detained 
later that year all had joined hunger strikes by detainees earlier 
this year 
among those released today were the rev sipho gogola of the 
interdenominational ministers association of southern africa lulu 
johnson former president of the congress of south african 
students and denis neer an official with the congress of south 
african trade unions 
all seven have held top positions in antiapartheid groups 
around port elizabeth one of the most militant black areas in the 
country however the highestranking opposition leaders in the 
area remain in detention 
since detainees began a hunger strike in january the government 
says it has freed more than 800 people detained without charge and 
that less than 100 remain imprisoned 
the government said previously that all emergency detainees had 
given up their hunger strikes there was no way to independently 
confirm that report 
more than 400 of the released detainees have been placed under 
restriction orders limiting their activities according to human 
rights groups 
an estimated 30000 people almost all black have been held 
without charge for varying lengths of time under the state of 
emergency 
the antiapartheid activists are fighting a system that 
establishes a racially segregated society in which the 28 million 
blacks have no vote in national affairs the countrys 5 million 
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts schools 
and health services 
