<TEXT>
the soviet union promised a 35nation eastwest 
conference on press freedom wednesday that it would review working 
conditions for moscowbased journalists and open its airways to 
foreign tv programs 
the chief us delegate accused four of the communist 
participants romania bulgaria east germany and czechoslovakia 
of ignoring the agreement on press and other freedoms that the 35 
countries signed in january at the conference on security and 
cooperation in europe 
the signatory countries varied from the united states where 
press freedom is enshrined in the constitution to romania where 
typewriters have to be licensed and police keep records of the 
typefaces 
the aim of this weeks meeting information forum is to monitor 
compliance with the agreement 
ambassador leonard h marks a former director of the us 
information agency and head of the american delegation said the 
soviet union had made substantial progress including stopping 
jamming foreign broadcasts but its media remained only 
semifree 
the concept that the east europeans and the soviets had that 
the government controls the press is now disappearing some 
nonofficial viewpoints are presented not all marks said in 
an interview with the associated press 
but were going to be behind them the objectives are to have 
a free press not a semifree press 
soviet deputy foreign minister vladimir petrovsky questioned by 
reporters at a news conference on why foreign correspondents were 
banned from the soviet republic of georgia during nationalist 
unrest this month said we will take this criticism very 
seriously 
we will work very hard to provide international standards for 
the working of journalists said petrovsky 
he said foreign reporters were banned from georgia where 20 
people were killed in disturbances because it could be dangerous 
for the correpondents 
in an address to the conference wednesday petrovsky said 
foreign correspondents can now travel more freely in the soviet 
union and were allowed more contact with soviet citizens 
glasnost means that every citizen should have the right to 
receive complete and reliable information on any public issue 
said petrovsky there are no limits to improving reporters 
working conditions 
he added that extensive work is under way in the soviet union 
to create optimal conditions to ensure free access to information 
including arranging subscriptions to foreign periodicals and 
reception of foreign tv broadcasts 
he acknowledged difficulties remained about receiving foreign tv 
signals in the soviet union using copying equipment access to 
audio and video information and buying foreign periodicals 
the existing obstacles and restrictions in this area will be 
removed as the overall democratization process in the ussr 
further unfolds 
marks said the four east bloc states he singled out have 
recognized the obligations of januarys vienna agreement but 
they have not fulfilled them 
he said the us delegation will press specific cases during 
closed sessions which start next week after four days of opening 
speeches by delegation chiefs 
our objective is not to be confrontational said marks we 
want to try to solve problems we dont need any more 
agreements on principles we need action 
the vienna agreement was the outcome of eastwest talks on human 
rights and free speech that began in helsinki in the 1970s 
