attackers ambushed and shot up the first 
truck convoy of a un famine relief effort intended to save 
100000 lives in the southern sudan war zone killing seven armed 
escorts un officials said wednesday 
they said a civilian driver and two assistants were wounded and 
radio reports from the scene identified the slain escorts as 
members of the rebel sudan peoples liberation army 
un officials in nairobi did not affix blame for the attack on 
the 14truck convoy but speculation centered on nomadic tribal 
warriors army soldiers or governmentsponsored militias operating 
against the rebels 
the attack occurred tuesday about 20 miles west of kapoeta a 
rebel base in southeastern sudan 50 miles north of the kenya 
border it was another setback for operation lifelinesudan the 
132 million un relief program plagued by delays caused by 
bureaucracy bad weather and equipment shortages 
relief officials said the trucks were carrying 100 tons of food 
medicine and other supplies to torit 100 miles west of kapoeta 
when they were halted by rocket and automatic weapons fire 
it was the first convoy to torit under the unsponsored effort 
to stockpile more than 100000 tons of supplies in southern sudan 
before heavy rains beginning next month make transport virtually 
impossible 
even before the attack un officials had conceded they 
probably could not meet their goals before the rainy season which 
lasts until november 
we think it is an isolated incident we dont think it 
represents a breach of agreement on the part of either party 
said diane weathers a un world food program spokeswoman in 
nairobi 
a statement issued in new york by james p grant personal 
representative of secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar for the 
project said the united nations would like to draw the worlds 
attention to the dangerous consequences that repetition of such 
action could have on the future of operation lifelinesudan 
operation lifeline began april 1 after agreement in march by the 
sudanese government and rebels to allow relief supplies through 
their lines for a month western relief organizations say up to 
half a million people died in southern sudan last year of 
starvation caused by the 6yearold civil war drought and floods 
rebels led by former army col john garang demand greater 
autonomy and more economic help for the blacks of the south most 
of whom are christians or animists from the arabs in the moslem 
north who control the government 
a french monitor for the world food program was riding with the 
convoy and reported the attack tuesday night to officials 
coordinating the relief operation from nairobi 
paul mitchell a un spokesman said the lead vehicle was 
destroyed by some sort of missile and the rebel escorts came 
under fire from automatic weapons 
he said the escorts were believed to be members of the sudan 
relief and rehabilitation association an agency of the rebel army 
ms weathers said they were armed 
mitchell said use of operation lifelines overland route to 
torit from kapoeta would be suspended indefinitely but an airlift 
to torit from entebbe uganda would begin friday 
operations officer vincent oreilly said torits population had 
grown from 3000 to 25000 as displaced southern sudanese seeking 
food and shelter arrived from the bush and was expected to reach 
50000 in a few weeks 
the united nations had planned to move 25000 tons of food and 
supplies from kenya to southern sudan before the rains but convoys 
have taken only 120 tons to kapoeta so far 
norwegian peoples aid in conjunction with world vision of 
monrovia calif and the us agency for international 
development has trucked several thousand tons of food to kapoeta 
since october in another relief effort 
an airlift from uganda operated by the world food program and 
catholic relief services has carried 3000 tons of food and other 
supplies to juba the southern provincial capital swollen by 
refugees to a population of 300000 
