<TEXT>
under the bright lights of a tent often 
used for basketball games in this seaside town about 1700 jewish 
emigres celebrated their first passover outside the soviet union 
for many who could not learn the rudiments of their faith in 
their officially atheist homeland the ceremony wednesday was the 
first real experience the holiday commemorating the release of the 
ancient israelites from bondage in egypt 
the emigres who await visas for the united states or other 
countries were guided through the service by rabbi hirsch rabiski 
who emigrated from the soviet union 15 years ago and now ministers 
to the estimated 4000 jews in ladispoli 
he carefully explained in russian the significance of the 
passover meal the seder and introduced the rituals the refugees 
at small tables with their families listened politely and some 
whispered questions to neighbors 
this is all so difficult to take in said a doctor from baky 
in azerbaijan province who identified herself only as yana she 
said she felt overwhelmed by so much knowledge about a faith she 
had always identified with but had not learned well 
the seder was paid for and organized by the american jewish 
joint distribution committee which cares for the emigres from 
arrival in austria through the transfer to italy the main us 
visa processing point to their departure weeks or months later 
