<TEXT>
daphne du maurier author of rebecca died 
wednesday at her home in cornwall the wildly beautiful english 
province in which she set many of her celebrated novels of romance 
and the supernatural she was 81 
her novels like rebecca frenchmans creek my cousin 
rachel and jamaica inn were household names in popular 
fiction and became hit movies 
the du maurier style vivid and gothic made for spinechilling 
films like alfred hitchcocks the birds from her short story 
and nicolas roegs dont look now from her novella 
dame daphne as she was known after being honored by queen 
elizabeth ii died in her sleep said her friend and legal 
executor monty bakermunton 
until about two weeks ago she had been fit enough for daily 
walks with her dog around par the cornish village where she had 
lived in widowed seclusion for 20 years 
daphne du maurier was born in london on may 13 1907 one of 
three daughters of the renowned actor sir gerald du maurier 
educated by private tutors in paris she was 21 when she 
published her first articles and short stories her first novel 
the loving spirit appeared in 1931 
the novel captivated a young british army major and led to a 
storybook courtship 
the officer frederick a m boy browning resolved to meet 
the young woman and journeyed to par to find her they met in 1932 
and married a few months later 
it was rather womans magaziney she remarked afterward 
in the same year she published her second novel ill never be 
young again jamaica inn a big seller followed in 1936 and 
then came rebecca 
rebecca about a young bride whose probing into the death of 
her husbands previous wife leads her into a frightening 
psychological labyrinth was published in 1938 and sold 1 million 
copies in hard cover alone it was reprinted 39 times launched 
laurence oliviers movie career opposite joan fontaine and was 
translated worldwide 
she became lady browning with the ennoblement of her husband 
who had been commander of british airborne forces in world war ii 
and then treasurer to prince philip husband of queen elizabeth ii 
in 1943 they rented menabilly the rambling often fogshrouded 
georgian manor which had inspired manderley the firedoomed 
mansion in rebecca 
oliver cromwells troops gutted the house during the english 
civil war and legend had it that a cavalier was bricked up alive 
in one of menabillys gray stone buttresses 
the writers hideaway was a gardeners hut where she said 
id sit for hours on end chainsmoking chewing mints and 
tapping away at my typewriter 
she would prowl the grounds of menabilly or answer stacks of fan 
mail when not at work on her writing 
her husband died in 1965 in 1969 dame daphne as she had 
become that year moved from menabilly to par with her two 
yorkshire terriers and rented another mansion kilmarth it is 
rather like death to have to leave she said despite her wealth 
she never owned a home 
at kilmarth she wrote the house on the strand her last 
novel was rule britannia published in 1972 growing pains 
a memoir of her early years appeared in 1981 and her introduction 
to a new book on cornwall will appear in the fall 
although always cheerful and kind to friends she preferred a 
secluded life i cant say i really like people she once 
remarked perhaps thats why i always preferred to create my own 
instead of mixing with real ones 
she waited until age 64 before consenting to be interviewed on 
tv 
bakermunton said she would be cremated later this week at a 
private ceremony with no flowers and only family friends her son 
and two daughters in accordance with her wishes 
</TEXT>
