<TEXT>
whittle communications lp wants to put short 
hardcover books by respected authors in the briefcases of americas 
corporate and civic leaders and is selling advertising space in 
the books to pay the bill 
the proposal disclosed tuesday stirred curiosity in the 
publishing community which has generally limited advertising in 
hardcover books to pitches for either the authors or the 
publishers other works 
whether it is a ridiculous idea that will fall on its face or 
be the wave of the future i cant tell yet said joni evans the 
publisher of random house 
nansey neiman publisher of warner books said she hasnt 
decided whether advertising in books would be good for business 
but she added as a reader im not sure i want to read a book 
and find an ad for baby powder or worse 
the knoxville tennbased whittle said tuesday it has signed 
david halberstam john kenneth galbraith and seven other wellknown 
authors for the first of what it says will be several sponsored 
book series 
it would be the first book publishing venture by the 
fastgrowing media concern which has specialized in creating 
magazines posters and television programs that sponsors may use to 
reach tightlydefined audiences such as new mothers pet owners or 
teens at school 
whittle which is 50 percentowned by the media giant time inc 
said it plans to publish the first book in what is tentatively 
called the larger agenda series later this year it plans five 
books a year 
the other authors signed by whittle are george gilder edward j 
epstein james atlas robert waterman richard holbrooke daniel 
seligman and william greider they are reportedly being paid an 
average of 60000 each 
among the topics epstein will write about michael milken the 
indicted junk bond pioneer holbrooke will explain why business 
people should care about foreign policy and greider will write 
about the financial system 
the books will run about 100 pages with 20 pages of advertising 
scattered among 80 pages of editorial text and will be sent for 
free to about 150000 people whittle considers opinion leaders 
christopher whittle chairman of whittle communications said 
the project resulted from research that showed many readers failed 
to read or finish books because the books were too long and they 
had too little time 
he said writers meanwhile wanted an outlet longer than 
magazines provide but shorter than fulllength books 
advertising support provided the financial bridge needed to 
support the shorter books he said 
greider reached in washington dc said liked getting a 
chance to reach what should be a pretty bluechip audience and 
had no problem with the type of advertising he expects would be 
included in the series 
if the book was studded with truss ads and hairrestoring ads 
and breast implant ads i could see how you might have some 
problems with it he said 
whittle plans to sell copies at bookstores nationwide six months 
after the free distribution and will sell them more cheaply than 
books without ads 
whittle officials declined to identify advertisers but a source 
familiar with the plans speaking on condition of anonymity said 
federal express co of memphis tenn will be the sole advertiser 
in the first series 
federal express spokesman jim coleman said that for competitive 
reasons the company does not comment on its advertising plans 
carolyn reidy president and publisher of avon books said 
paperbacks once routinely carried ads two decades ago but the 
practice was phased out because of postal regulations and protests 
from authors i dont think there will be a rush to do it 
again she said 
whittle said he hoped to be publishing up to 40 books a year 
generating 50 million in annual revenue for his company in five 
years the company had 150 million in revenue last year 
