oil futures prices surged in early trading today 
as concern spread that a north sea oil explosion could disrupt 
petroleum deliveries 
on the new york mercantile exchange the may contract for west 
texas intermediate the benchmark grade of crude oil had jumped 
121 a barrel to 2272 at about 11 am edt the contract closed 
at 2151 on tuesday 
details are still vague but theres a possibility that some 
companies arent able to deliver on cargos due a week from today 
said ed ryan energy broker with dean witter reynolds inc this 
is impacting the market in a very big way 
the explosion and fire on the small oil cormorant alpha platform 
owned by shell uk exploration and production on tuesday shut down 
the north sea brent oil field interrupting production of nearly 
500000 barrels a day of oil officials said today 
the cormorant is a gathering station the brent crude must 
flow through this one smaller station said bob baker oil 
analyst with prudentialbache securities inc 
shell officials were expected to examine the damage today and 
decide how long the pipelines would remain closed analysts said 
energy brokers said the timing of the event following the 
alaskan oil spill could drive prices significantly higher 
the spill off the alaskan coast on march 24 closed down oil 
shipping lanes and disrupted the flow of oil to refineries in the 
united states for several days since then prices of both crude 
and refined products have risen by more than 10 cents 
crude prices have risen nearly 80 percent since last october 
when the organization of petroleum exporting countries decided to 
reduce oil production 
in addition problems with other north sea oil facilities and 
lower production by the united states have helped push prices 
higher 
