<TEXT>
shearson lehman hutton inc said wednesday it 
lost 15 million in the first quarter attributing the 90 million 
decline from last year to sluggish wall street business activity 
and higher interest rates 
shearson is the fifth investment firm to report a loss or lower 
earnings in the last week in addition drexel burnham lambert inc 
said wednesday it is selling its retail brokerage unit in part 
because of a business decline 
shearson said the loss for the quarter compared with a 75 
million profit or 75 cents a share in the same 1988 period 
the firm said the decline reflects a 352 million pretax 
writedown of mcorp securities held by the firm lower investment 
banking revenue and lower net interest income 
the decline came despite an increase in revenue to 3 billion 
from 25 billion a year ago 
the disappointing results for the quarter reflect the 
continuing low level of investor participation in the financial 
markets and the impact of higher interest rates shearson 
chairman peter a coehn said in a statement 
shearson said it is continuing cost control efforts 
including an agreement to sell a shareholder services group and 
negotiations to sell an asset management subsidiary 
shearson said investment banking revenue for the quarter totaled 
243 million a 319 perent drop from 357 million a year ago the 
firm said the decline reflects the industrywide slowdown in 
underwriting merger and acquisition activity 
commission revenues increased 95 percent to 436 million from 
398 million a year ago revenues from marketmaking and principal 
transactions fell 96 percent to 319 million from 353 million in 
the 1988 quarter 
the firm also showed a 712 percent drop in net interest income 
to 19 million from 66 million a year ago blaming a rise in 
shortterm rates that have often outpaced longterm ones 
american express co owns a controlling stake in shearson 
