at a luncheon wednesday with the american chamber of commerce in 
japan pickens argued that corporate buyouts helped put the us 
economy back on its feet in the 1980s by ousting ineffective 
management and making its companies more competitive 
what happened in the us in the 1980s will find its way to 
the japanese business community in the 1990s he said 
analysts in tokyo say pickens visit is a challenge to basic 
thinking in japans business community that a company belongs to 
its employees not its shareholders 
pickens gained fame and fortune in the united states by buying 
and reorganizing companies and often purging company executives 
arguing that bad managers dont give shareholders the returns they 
deserve 
he said in tokyo wednesday that his shareholders rights 
movement would soon spread to japan 
shareholders rights will become a worldwide issue he added 
but many japanese businessmen and some foreign critics believe 
that the american emphasis on return to shareholders has caused 
us companies to lose competitiveness to japanese companies 
japanese companies dont generally have to answer to 
shareholders with shortterm profits they can focus on longerterm 
