on other markets oil futures posted steep gains livestock and 
meat futures prices tumbled and precious metals were slightly lower 
wheat settled unchanged to 4 cents higher with the contract for 
delivery in may at 411 a bushel corn was 2 cents to 4 cents 
lower with may at 273 a bushel oats were 1 cents to 2 cents 
lower with may at 197 a bushel soybeans were 3 cents to 11 
cents lower with may at 745 a bushel 
welcome to the weather market said ted mao a new 
yorkbased grain specialist with shearson lehman hutton inc 
referring to the recent volatility in the grain markets 
corn and soybean planting has barely begun but the grain markets 
are extremely sensitive to weather changes because last years 
drought lowered us grain stockpiles another drought year could 
drain stocks down to critical levels and cause prices to skyrocket 
some private meteorologists who had been predicting dry weather 
for the rest of this week in iowa and northwestern illinois put 
more rain into their noon forecasts on wednesday prompting heavy 
selling of corn and soybean contracts 
after the close the national weather service issued a new 
sixto10 day forecast calling for abovenormal rainfall in the 
western midwest and normal precipitation in the regions central 
and eastern portions which could prompt further selling of corn 
and soybean futures on thursday 
the irony is that most experts agree that beyond 72 hours the 
degree of accuracy in a forecast drops geometrically mao said 
and yet everybody pays attention to those forecasts because there 
isnt anything else to trade on 
unleaded gasoline prices surged on the new york mercantile 
exchange leading the crude oil and heating oil markets higher 
following tuesdays american petroleum institute report of 
substantial reductions in us supplies of crude and gasoline 
further buying was spurred by reports that the shell oil cos 
british subsidiary had advise clients of possible shipment delays 
for north sea crude oil following the shutdown late tuesday of a 
damaged oil platform 
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 110 
higher with may at 2261 a barrel heating oil was 53 cent to 71 
cent higher with may at 5333 cents a gallon unleaded gasoline was 
75 cent to 120 cents higher with may at 7462 cents a gallon 
the sharp losses in livestock and meat futures on the chicago 
mercantile exchange were due more to profittaking and technical 
factors than to wednesdays weaker cash markets analysts said 
trading activity has grown cautious ahead of fridays quarterly 
agriculture department cattleonfeed report which is expected to 
show firstquarter placements of cattle on feedlots to be 3 percent 
to 10 percent above the first quarter of 1988 
