american telephone amp telegraph co announced a 
206 percent increase in firstquarter profit wednesday thrust 
ahead by an expensive restructuring last year that produced its 
first annual loss 
the phone giant achieved the improved results despite intense 
competition across its range of businesses robert e allen 
chairman and chief executive told shareholders at the companys 
104th annual meeting 
were seeing new vigor in our longdistance business and 
strong growth in international sales of products and services 
allen said 
the stock rose 37 cents a share to 3350 in consolidated new 
york stock exchange trading 
shareholders rejected a pair of shareholder proposals on 
affirmative action one to strengthen it and one to stop it also 
rejected were proposals to get more information on atampts lobbying 
and on its involvement in star wars defense contracts 
atampt said it earned 594 million or 55 cents a share in the 
first three months of 1989 up from 492 million or 46 cents a 
share a year earlier revenue rose 32 percent to 866 billion 
from 839 billion a year earlier 
earnings would have risen even more if the company had not 
adopted a more aggressive method of depreciating the value of its 
assets the change cut 88 million from firstquarter profits 
atampt lost 167 billion last year the result of a huge 
accounting charge that covered the cost of accelerating its 
transition to modern digital technology 
as part of the restructuring the company said last year it was 
scrapping outdated analog phone equipment and moving retiring or 
laying off 16000 employees 
although the charge produced a loss last year it is adding to 
profitability this year by lowering the companys payroll and 
depreciation expenses 
allen declined to predict profits for the rest of the year but 
said he would not be surprised if they kept up the same pace 
this is not an aberration at least based on our business plan 
atampt is no longer the worlds largest company since the 1984 
bell system breakup but it remains the most widely held stock in 
the country with 26 million shareowners 
allen told 2360 shareholders in radio city music hall that the 
company was getting closer to being able to raise its quarterly 
dividend which has been stuck at 30 cents a share since 
divestiture 
richard toole a merrill lynch amp co analyst predicted the 
dividend might be raised early next year 
allen was elected chairman the night before the 1988 annual 
meeting in denver following the death a day earlier of chairman 
james e olson olsons unexpected death cast a pall over that 
gathering 
aside from the emotional aspect i feel much more 
comfortable after a year on the job allen told a news 
conference i have a good sense of the business the people 
whats important where were going 
in longdistance allen said aggressive advertising and sales 
promotions an expanded sales force and increased regulatory 
flexibility were paying off 
product sales grew 45 percent mainly because of higher 
international sales of telecommunications network equipment and 
increases in microelectronic components sales to the federal 
government and some computer products also sales of the newly 
acquired paradyne corp were included in the results for the first 
time 
shareholders rejected a proposal by the national alliance a 
whitesupremacist organization to phase out aspects of atampts 
affirmative action program which are directed toward recruiting 
employing or promoting individuals from any particular racial or 
ethnic group 
however 81 percent of the shares were voted in favor 
entitling the group to resubmit it next year a proposal by an atampt 
employee alex tillman to strengthen and provide details on the 
affirmative action received support from 47 percent of the shares 
falling below the 6 percent cutoff for resubmission 
allen said atampt management opposed both proposals but reserved 
his main criticism for the national alliance one which he 
described as an insult to atampt employees 
